{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564933"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:20:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:20:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17169"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17169","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17169"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.65,0.01,0.04,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9859"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68958"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9859","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9859"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17169"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54415"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"2257"},{"type":"tags","id":"2496"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"3804"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23110"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43690"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44808"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68958","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68958"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with three months of progressive dyspnoea and dry cough. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She has never smoked. She works as an accountant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears short of breath at rest. Her pulse rate is 95/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is dullness to percussion and reduced breath sounds at the right base. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA chest radiograph shows a right-sided pleural effusion. CT chest reveals a 4 cm mass in the right lower lobe with pleural metastases. A pleural biopsy confirms adenocarcinoma of lung origin.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following clinical features is most strongly associated with this presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Current heavy smoking","Female never-smoker status","Male sex","Older age","Previous asbestos exposure"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with lung adenocarcinoma with several notable clinical features. \u003Cstrong\u003EFemale never-smoker status\u003C/strong\u003E is strongly associated with a distinct molecular subtype of lung adenocarcinoma that tends to respond well to targeted therapies. This pattern is particularly common in younger women who have never smoked.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECurrent heavy smoking\u003C/strong\u003E is more commonly associated with squamous cell carcinoma of the lung and carries different molecular characteristics. While smoking is the strongest risk factor for lung cancer overall, certain subtypes are more common in never-smokers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMale sex\u003C/strong\u003E is generally associated with a higher overall risk of lung cancer, but the specific subtype seen in this case is more common in women.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOlder age\u003C/strong\u003E is typically associated with lung cancer in general, with the median age at diagnosis being around 70 years. However, the subtype suggested by this case can affect younger patients, particularly women.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrevious asbestos exposure\u003C/strong\u003E is more commonly associated with mesothelioma or other types of lung cancer, rather than the adenocarcinoma subtype presented in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these clinical associations is important as they can help guide molecular testing and treatment selection. Different subtypes of lung cancer have distinct molecular profiles that influence prognosis and response to therapy. In particular, never-smokers with lung cancer often have better responses to certain targeted therapies compared to smokers.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lung adenocarcinoma in never-smokers is more common in women and has distinct molecular features.","Molecular testing guides treatment selection in advanced non-small cell lung cancer.","Clinical features such as sex, smoking status, and age help predict molecular subtypes of lung cancer."],"references":["Hendriks LEL, Remon J, Faivre-Finn C, Garassino MC, Heymach JV, Kerr KM, et al. Non-small-cell lung cancer. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2024 Sep 26;10(1):1\u201322."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54415"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17169"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54415"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T19:17:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T19:19:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9859"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68958"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"p